The behavior is very random and not expected but can be reproduced. For example here is my extension.ts:

``` typescript
import * as vscode from 'vscode'; 

import { FoobarCompletion } from "./foobar"

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
    vscode.languages.registerCompletionItemProvider("barfoo", new FoobarCompletion());
    vscode.languages.registerCompletionItemProvider("foobar", new FoobarCompletion());
}
```

FoobarCompletion is just resolving some words (a-z) using a `Thenable<vscode.CompletionItem[]>`

When now trying to auto complete a file which is named `test.foobar` it wont work on whitespaces but `test.barfoo` would work. When switching the completion item providers around then the reverse will happen. Note that this bug only occurs when there is some content in the file already.

foobar.ts for reproducing: https://gist.github.com/WebFreak001/79e5d150cb78c833875d
package.json for reproducing: https://gist.github.com/WebFreak001/073847d7e96dde6567b6

When now using that code and assuming in file test.barfoo and in test.foobar is the following text:

```
banana {
    |
}
```

(`|` = cursor)

When trying to complete now it will only work for the .barfoo file but not for the .foobar file.

I am using "npm link ../../lib/my-lib" to symlink a local module that is shared across several apps into the "node_modules" directory of each of the apps. This is nice for developing the shared lib in combination with all the apps.

```
// a standard npm module, can't navigate to its definition
var shortid = require('shortid');
// some functions from a symlink-ed local module inside node_modules, can't navigate to it either
var ModelMountUtils = require('@ipp/loopback-lib').ModelMountUtils;
var RemoteMethodUtils = require('@ipp/loopback-lib').RemoteMethodUtils;
```

VS-Code does not allow me to navigate to this shared libraries' code by pressing F12 or "Go to definition". The same applies for all other npm modules inside the node_modules directory.

Is this restricted functionality intentional ? or should it be working and I am running to a JS parsing bug that prevents the "Go to definition" to do its work ?
If the "Go to definition" feature is not supposed to work for all things "node_modules" ... could we integrate an exception for symlink directories inside node_modules ?

Thanks
